Title: The Quiet Period Goes out with a Bang 
Abstract:
 We examine the expiration of the IPO quiet period, which occurs after the
 25-super-th calendar day following the offering. For IPOs during 1996 to
 2000, we find that analyst coverage is initiated immediately for 76
 percent of these firms, almost always with a favorable rating. Initiated
 firms experience a five-day abnormal return of 4.1 percent versus 0.1
 percent for firms with no coverage. The abnormal returns are concentrated
 in the days just before the quiet period expires. Abnormal returns are
 much larger when coverage is initiated by multiple analysts. It does not
 matter whether a recommendation comes from the lead underwriter or not. Copyright 2003 by the American Finance Association. 
