Title: Dynamic Asset Allocation with Event Risk 
Abstract:
 Major events often trigger abrupt changes in stock prices and volatility.
 We study the implications of jumps in prices and volatility on investment
 strategies. Using the event-risk framework of Duffie, Pan, and Singleton
 (2000), we provide analytical solutions to the optimal portfolio problem.
 Event risk dramatically affects the optimal strategy. An investor facing
 event risk is less willing to take leveraged or short positions. The
 investor acts as if some portion of his wealth may become illiquid and the
 optimal strategy blends both dynamic and buy-and-hold strategies. Jumps in
 prices and volatility both have important effects. Copyright 2003 by the American Finance Association. 
