Author-Name: Eugene A. Pilotte 
Author-Workplace-Name: Rutgers University, School of Business Camden 
Title: Capital Gains, Dividend Yields, and Expected Inflation 
Abstract:
 One explanation for the negative relationship between short-horizon stock
 returns and inflation is that inflation proxies (inversely) for expected
 future real output. In this paper, I examine the possibility that
 inflation also proxies for variation in real price/dividend ratios (excess
 returns). I show that when the covariance between real price/dividend
 ratios and inflation is nonzero, the relationship between returns and
 expected inflation differs for the two components of returns: dividend
 yields and capital gains returns. My empirical evidence demonstrates that
 dividend yields and capital gains are related differently to expected
 inflation in U.S. and foreign markets. Copyright 2003 by the American Finance Association. 
